          <avActivityHighlights>Weak layers in the old snowpack necessitate caution and restraint. In particular shady places that are protected from the wind above approximately 2800 m: &lt;br/&gt; As the moisture increases moist small and medium sized avalanches are possible.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>Dry avalanches can be released in deeper layers, in particular by large additional loads. The avalanches can in isolated cases reach large size. &lt;br/&gt; As a consequence of warming during the day, the likelihood of moist and wet avalanches being released will increase in particular on steep slopes below approximately 2600 m. &lt;br/&gt;</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>The upper section of the snowpack is well consolidated and its surface has a crust that is strong in many cases. In particular sunny slopes and below approximately 2800 m: &lt;br/&gt; Precarious weak layers exist in the old snowpack especially on steep northwest, north and northeast facing slopes. Several medium-sized and, in isolated cases, large avalanches are possible.</snowpackStructureComment>
